  <article class="measure py-10">
    <p class="small-caps text-muted">About</p>
    <h1 class="issue-title">Built for operators who need to know what's actually changing.</h1>

    <div class="prose-frontier mt-8">
      <p>
        Bitter Frontier reads projects across the coding-agent stack together:
        what general agents just made cheaper, what became the new bottleneck,
        and where operators should spend scarce human attention.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two named ideas guide that read. <a href="/bitter-lesson/">Bitter Lesson Maxing</a> means
        building where improving general agents compound your advantage, not where their next release erases it.
        <a href="/amdahls-law/">Amdahl Maxing</a> means treating human attention as the scarce serial
        resource and spending it where judgment changes the outcome.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not a newsletter summarizing blog posts. Claims trace back to
        primary sources: commits, releases, versioned documentation, security
        advisories, or described reproducible observations. A signal should
        change what you build, delegate, configure, test, measure, keep human,
        or stop relying on. The evidence chain is public and auditable.
      </p>
      <p>
        Software helps gather and check the source record. Michael Ruescher sets
        the editorial doctrine, verifies the reading, and decides what deserves
        publication. Automation expands coverage; editorial judgment stays
        accountable. The <a href="/runs/">research trail</a> preserves what was
        read, what was found, and what the review caught.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bitter Frontier is published by <a href="https://bitter.sh">Bitter</a>, which builds a harness-agnostic operating
        environment for coding agents. The publication has its own method: claims need sources, and signals need operator
        consequences.
      </p>
      <p>
        Founder and editor Michael Ruescher previously built a
        <a href="https://blueshift.com/blog/phasehandoff-long-horizon-agents/">long-horizon agent at Blueshift</a>.
        That work led to the layer decision behind Bitter: the company is betting that provider harnesses should remain
        replaceable while the operating environment and accumulated company state stay durable. Frontier is the upstream
        intelligence function that follows from that decision. Read the <a href="/letter/">pinned founder's letter</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

